Part I - Exploratory Data Analysis: Prosper Loan Dataset¶

by Joseph Etim¶

Introduction¶

This data set contains 113,937 loans with 81 variables on each loan, including loan amount, borrower rate (or interest rate), current loan status, borrower income, and many others.

# Creating a function to plot the number of null values
def plot_nas(df: pd.DataFrame):
    if df.isnull().sum().sum() != 0:
        na_df = (df.isnull().sum() / len(df)) * 100      
        na_df = na_df.drop(na_df[na_df == 0].index).sort_values(ascending= True)
        missing_data = pd.DataFrame({'Missing Ratio %' :na_df})
        missing_data.plot(kind = "line", color = 'green')
        plt.ylabel("Percentage of records missing", fontsize = 10)
        plt.xlabel("Columns with Missing Values", fontsize = 10)
        plt.show()
    else:
        print('No Null found')
        

plot_nas(loandata)
plot_width, plot_height = (20, 15)
plt.rcParams['figure.figsize'] = (plot_width, plot_height)

EXPLORATORY DATA ANALYSIS¶

Using summary statistics and graphical representations, exploratory data analysis will be performed in this section to study the data in order to discover insights and form data driven opinions for decision making.

The analysis would be divided into three categories: univariate, bivariate, and multivariate.

UNIVARIATE ANALYSIS¶

Analyzing just one variable is referred to as univariate analysis. To comprehend the distribution of values for a single variable, univariate analysis is used.

I will start by looking into the number of loan listings. According to Law Insider, Loan Listing means a request by a Borrower to borrow money on the terms of a Loan. The process of analyzing one variable is regarded as Univariate. To comprehend the distribution of values for a single variable, univariate analysis would be deployed to get few insights.

The following inputs would be looked at

  • The loan amount collected based on employment status
  • Distrubitions of borrowers based on state
  • Borrowing rate based on occupation
  • Loan amount that is frequently requested
  • The most loan term required by borrowers
  • The distriution of borrowers based on their Prosper score

# To view Tthe loan amount collected based on employment status
def countploty(y):
    plt.figure(figsize = [12,12])
    base_color = sns.color_palette("dark")[9]
    sns.countplot(data=loandata, y = y, color = base_color, order = loandata[y].value_counts().index)

# to plot the count plot
countploty('EmploymentStatus')
plt.xlabel('LoanOriginalAmount', fontsize = 12)
plt.title('Count of Loan Amount Per Employment Status', fontsize = 14)
plt.show();

base_color = sns.color_palette("dark")[9]
sns.countplot(data=loandata, x = 'ProsperScore', color = base_color, order = order)
plt.xlabel('Prosper Score', fontsize = 12)
plt.title('Count of Borrowers per Prosper Score', fontsize = 14)
plt.show();
  • From the visuals we can tell that most of the borrowers are people whose prosper score fall between 4, 6 and 8 while the he lowest prosper score is 1 and 11.

# Visualization to check for any relationship between the loan amount with respect to the Borrowers income bracket and Loan status
plt.figure(figsize = (17,8))
group = loandata.groupby(['IncomeRange', 'LoanStatus'])['LoanOriginalAmount'].mean()
group = group.reset_index(name = 'Average Loan Amount')
group = group.pivot(index = 'IncomeRange', columns = 'LoanStatus', values = 'Average Loan Amount')
sns.heatmap(group, cmap = 'viridis')
plt.title('HeatMap Showing the Average Loan Amount for each Income range and Loan Status', fontsize = 16);
  • It can be seen from the chart that borrowers with high income ranges ask for high loan amounts. The borrowers that received the largest loan amounts are in the Current Loan Status and earn between $100,000 and more annually.
